Title: The Implications of ADA Litigation for Employers: A Review of Federal Appellate Court Decisions
Author-Name: Lee, Barbara A.
Abstract: Analysis of litigation outcomes indicates that most plaintiffs who sue under the Americans with Disabilities Act are unsuccessful. Equal Employment Opportunity Commission enforcement data and six years of federal appellate court decisions were reviewed, as well as recent rulings of the United States Supreme Court. The courts are interpreting the ADA very narrowly, and very few plaintiffs prevail. The results of this research suggest that if employers engage in an individualized assessment of whether an individual is protected by the law and whether the requested accommodation is reasonable, legal liability will be minimized. © 2001 John Wiley & Sons, Inc.
Year: 2001
Volume: 40
Issue: 1
Keywords: 
File-url: http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/hrm.4014/abstract
Journal: Human Resource Management

